		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05dd682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>2:18.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Form of testimony and questions</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Both <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER611" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I97310db074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 611(a)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-611" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I97310db174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-611</cite.query>
						<?page no="22"?> give courts broad discretion over the mode and order of interrogating witnesses. <eos/>
						<bos/>The court may allow witnesses to respond to specific questions, general questions, leading questions, or testify in a narrative form. <eos/>
						<bos/>A leading question is one so framed as to suggest the desired answer.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a2977074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Generally, leading questions are proper only during cross-examination, but the court may grant or withhold this form of questioning during direct[<footnote.reference refid="I76a2be8074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] or cross-examination when the conduct of the witness or justice shall require it. <eos/>
						<bos/>Both federal and state courts allow parties to expedite a trial by asking leading questions on direct examination on undisputed, preliminary, or collateral matters.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a2be8174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] Also, at the court&apos;s discretion, a party may use leading questions to examine an adverse party or one identified with an adverse party.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a2be8274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2017487349" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9733309274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Bell v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a2e59074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals affirmed that the trial court acted within its discretion by allowing a prosecutor to use leading questions during direct examination of a child victim. <eos/>
						<bos/>The victim was 14 years old at the time of trial, was often unresponsive, spoke very quietly, and exhibited signs of timidity or fear.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>This discretion extends to allowing leading questions on direct of witnesses who are nervous, ignorant, or hostile.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a2e59174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1983128122" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9734902274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Mercer v. Woodard</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a30ca074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] the court properly forced a defendant to ask direct examination questions of a plaintiff whom it called as a witness during presentation of the defense case and properly allowed plaintiff&apos;s counsel to ask leading questions.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2011193571" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I97357a8274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Dumas v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a30ca174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] the court allowed leading questions on direct for a witness who had difficulty speaking English.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="23"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Since the purpose of redirect examination is to elicit evidence which explains, refutes or qualifies matters raised during cross-examination, both Georgia and federal courts allow leading questions as a necessary tool to direct the witness&apos; attention to the exact subject matter of the testimony sought.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a333b074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-611" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I9736da1074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-611</cite.query> guarantees, <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“the right of a thorough and sifting cross-examination shall belong to every party as to the witnesses called against him. <eos/>
						<bos/>If several parties to the same case have distinct interests, each may exercise this right.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> Although federal courts and many state courts limit the scope of cross-examination to issues addressed on direct examination or affecting the credibility of the witness,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a333b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] Georgia has retained its “free” common-law based rule regarding the scope of cross-examination.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a35ac074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] Under the free rule, a party may cross-examine witness about any subject relevant to any issue in the case, including facts relating solely to the examiner&apos;s case or affirmative defense.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a35ac174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] The trial court has broad discretion to curtail the extent of cross-examination if the inquiry is not relevant.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a35ac274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“Like most questions about the admissibility of evidence, the scope of cross-examination is committed in the first instance to the sound discretion of the trial court, and … a limitation of cross-examination [is reviewed] only for an abuse of that discretion.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I76a381d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] Moreover, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-611" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I973ccd8074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-611(a)</cite.query> gives the trial court reasonable control over the mode and order of interrogating witnesses. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2043639147" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I973ccd8374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Jordan v. State,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I76a381d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="24"?>] the Court of Appeals refused to find an abuse of discretion where the defense called the victim to testify during its case-in-chief and the trial court denied the request because the victim had testified for the prosecution and was thoroughly cross-examined by defense counsel at that time.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Also, both federal and Georgia courts must protect a witness from harsh or unfair treatment by counsel.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a381d274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">16</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1949104432" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I973e2d1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Loomis v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a3a8e074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">17</footnote.reference>] the court properly admonished defendant&apos;s counsel for speaking too loudly when he questioned a 12-year-old witness. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2048595473" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000999" ID="I973f177174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Elkins v. State,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I76a3a8e174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">18</footnote.reference>] the court allowed a juvenile witness to break for the evening over objection. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Court of Appeals found it was proper, given the court&apos;s reasoning that it was past the time the jurors should have been dismissed for the evening, and because the witness stated he needed a break.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2018991818" w-seq-number="00040" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I973fdac274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Butler v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a3cff074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">19</footnote.reference>] the court sustained the state&apos;s objection of the defense counsel&apos;s fourth question to a witness regarding whether he would tell a lie when the witness had answered “no” to the previous three questions.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Counsel who called the witness has a duty to protect the witness with proper and timely objections under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00042" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-623" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I9740770074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-6-623</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00043" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-611" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I9740770174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">24-6-611</cite.query>, but this duty must be balanced against the parties&apos; right to a thorough and sifting cross-examination.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a3cff174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">20</footnote.reference>] The court may not limit the cross-examination of a witness to matters elicited on direct examination[<footnote.reference refid="I76a3cff274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">21</footnote.reference>] nor may the court deny a party cross-examination entirely.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a3f70074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">22</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1997050801" w-seq-number="00047" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9741fda274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Druitt v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a3f70174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">23</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals upheld the trial court&apos;s refusal to permit a driving under the influence (DUI) defendant to require a police officer to demonstrate the “one-leg stand” test on cross-examination because the officer&apos;s ability to perform the test was not relevant to a determination of whether the defendant had been driving while impaired.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>If relevant, a party may cross-examine the opposing party based upon that party&apos;s unsworn pleadings.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a41e1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">24</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1991124028" w-seq-number="00050" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I97435d3274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Davis v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a41e1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">25</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="25"?>] the court ruled that the defense had no right to cross-examine an investigating officer, after the state introduced the officer&apos;s report, regarding a statement made by defendant contained within his report.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The biases, prejudices, or ulterior motives of a witness are always a proper subject of cross-examination. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1993052369" w-seq-number="00052" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9744208274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Hurston v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a4452074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">26</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals reversed the defendant&apos;s conviction because the trial court did not allow him to cross-examine the state&apos;s key witness about criminal charges pending against him. <eos/>
						<bos/>However, the Georgia Supreme Court upheld a conviction where the trial court prohibited the defense from cross-examining a witness regarding his immigration status.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a4452174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">27</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under the new Code, any party may impeach the credibility of a witness regardless of who called him.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a4452274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">28</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A party may call an opposing lawyer to the witness stand for cross-examination if he does not offer proof to support his claims about a witness. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1945195648" w-seq-number="00056" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I9745f54174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>U.S. v. Pugliese</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a46c3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">29</footnote.reference>] a lawyer asked a witness if she had been hospitalized for mental problems, but then offered no proof to support the question when she denied that she had been. <eos/>
						<bos/>Judge Learned Hand held that the court properly allowed the opposing party to call this lawyer to the stand for cross-examination.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A party may waive cross-examination of a witness expressly or by failing to object to a ruling of the court.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a46c3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">30</footnote.reference>] If a witness testifies on direct examination but is unable to continue through cross examination, then the court may strike the witness&apos; direct testimony or declare a mistrial. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1910012526" w-seq-number="00059" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I974754d274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Gale v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76a46c3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">31</footnote.reference>] a witness testified on direct, but then collapsed before she could be cross-examined. <eos/>
						<bos/>The defendant declined the court&apos;s offer to declare a mistrial and moved to strike the witness&apos; direct testimony. <eos/>
						<bos/>The court denied the motion, but the defendant failed to object, thereby waiving his right to cross-examination. <eos/>
						<bos/>Often this situation arises when a witness claims his privilege against self-incrimination and refuses to answer a question on cross-examination. <eos/>
						<bos/>If a witness&apos; claim of privilege on cross-examination prevents inquiry into the details of his direct examination testimony, then the court should strike the witness&apos; direct examination testimony in whole or in part.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I76a4934074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">32</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>With Georgia&apos;s adoption of the federal rule in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00066" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-7-705" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I97499ec074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<?page no="26"?>O.C.G.A. § 24-7-705</cite.query>, an expert witness does not need to be questioned using hypothetical questions. <eos/>
						<bos/>However, if counsel chooses to use a hypothetical question, then it must be based on evidence used at trial.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block><?page no="22"?>
			<footnote ID="I76a2977074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1976135707" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I973134c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ealey v. State, 139 Ga. App. 110, 227 S.E.2d 902 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I76a2be8074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>The appellate court rarely interferes with the trial court&apos;s discretion in this matter. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1973126954" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9731d10274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Daniels v. State, 230 Ga. 126, 195 S.E.2d 900 (1973)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I76a2be8174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>3</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1979183982" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I97321f2274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Shirley v. State, 148 Ga. App. 96, 97, 251 S.E.2d 57 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I76a2be8274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>4</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="2022918269" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0006538" w-pinpoint-page="588" ID="I9732945174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jaffe v. Bank of America, N.A., 395 Fed. Appx. 583, 588 (11th Cir. 2010)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I76a2e59074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>5</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
