			<footnote ID="I76a333b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>10</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER611" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I9738fcf074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 611(b)</cite.query> provides that cross-examination <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“shall be limited to the subject matter of the direct examination and matters affecting the credibility of the witness.”<eos/>
							<bos/>
							<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> The court does retain the discretion to allow a party to inquire into additional matters, but must proceed as if on direct examination. <eos/>
							<bos/>Many district courts have been reversed for unduly limiting the scope of cross-examination. <eos/>
							<bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1976146172" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I9738fcf274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. Segal, 534 F.2d 578, 2 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 542 (3d Cir. 1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1977104455" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I9738fcf674d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. Callahan, 551 F.2d 733, 1 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 881 (6th Cir. 1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1978103170" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000106" ID="I9738fcfb74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. Wolfson, 573 F.2d 216, 45 A.L.R. Fed. 625 (5th Cir. 1978)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018091" w-serial-number="1978118643" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I9738fcfd74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. Jackson, 576 F.2d 46 (5th Cir. 1978)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
